look into how attitudes towards abortion among women in an urban Malaysian context would affect their welfare through the lens of social justice. A mixed methods approach will be used for this study – working with self-administered questionnaires and in-depth interviews. The results will be used to understand the needs, attitudes and current situation of mothers in Malaysia. A qualitative analysis of the interview transcripts and elaboration of the quantitative findings will provide information on the effects of attitudes towards abortion on these women’s well-being. The resultant policies from this research will acknowledge the complexity and variety of particular scenarios involved in determining the wellbeing of a woman or a child, in order to realise a framework of social justice on women’s right to abortion within the Malaysian context.
